{"title":"DetCLIPv2: Scalable Open-Vocabulary Object Detection Pre-training via Word-Region Alignment","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Open-vocabulary detection needs to learn from massive web image–text pairs, but captions lack instance-level boxes, VL distillation suffers domain gaps, and pseudo-labeling limits accuracy and scalability.","method":"DetCLIPv2 performs end-to-end joint pre-training on detection, grounding, and raw image–text pairs under a unified formulation, learning fine-grained word–region alignment directly from captions. For each noun phrase, it matches the best region proposal via a max-similarity (1-to-1) set alignment and optimizes a text-to-image contrastive loss only, which mitigates the partial-label problem in web data. It selects proposals for contrast by scoring regions with the maximum similarity to all concepts in the local batch, focusing on text-relevant regions. Alternating data types during training creates a flywheel between localization and recognition, and using low-resolution inputs for web pairs enables efficient scaling (e.g., 13× more pairs with similar training time)."},{"problem":"During weakly supervised phases with grounding or image–text pairs, the detector’s regression branch lacks direct supervision and does not benefit from VL objectives, hurting localization.","method":"DetCLIPv2 inserts a lightweight deformable convolution at the start of the classification head that uses features from the regression head to compute offsets and modulation, allowing gradients from classification to flow into regression. This improves spatial aggregation and localization ability when training without box supervision, delivering clear AP gains with negligible training-time overhead."}]}
